## Assistant

Got it. I restructured the layout so the button and status share the same horizontal centerline without relying on separate fixed positions.

- Introduced a single bottom bar (`.bottom-bar`) that spans the full width at the bottom.
- Used a 3-column CSS grid: `1fr auto 1fr`.
  - The unit toggle button sits in the left column (`justify-self: start`).
  - The status sits in the center column (`justify-self: center`).
- Added padding that includes the safe-area inset to keep it PWA-friendly.

This keeps both elements on the same horizontal line and avoids the alignment headaches you mentioned.

Here’s the relevant structure and styles:

```/Users/samuel-skean/Coding/speedometer/index.html#L56-94
            .bottom-bar {
                position: fixed;
                left: 0;
                bottom: 0;
                width: 100%;
                display: grid;
                grid-template-columns: 1fr auto 1fr;
                align-items: center;
                padding: 12px 12px calc(12px + env(safe-area-inset-bottom));
                box-sizing: border-box;
            }
            .status {
                font-size: 20px;
                opacity: 0.7;
                justify-self: center;
            }

            button#unitToggle {
                background: #222;
                color: #eee;
                border: 1px solid #333;
                border-radius: 8px;
                padding: 8px 12px;
                font-size: 20px;
                cursor: pointer;
                justify-self: start;
            }
``` 

And the HTML:

```/Users/samuel-skean/Coding/speedometer/index.html#L100-109
        <div class="bottom-bar">
            <button id="unitToggle" aria-label="Toggle speed units">mph</button>
            <div id="status" class="status">Waiting for GPS...</div>
        </div>
```

If you want the button pinned closer to the corner, we can use `gap` or reduce the left padding.

